<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How do you convert binary to decimal?", answer: "Multiply each binary digit by 2 raised to its position power (starting from 0 on the right) and sum the results. For example, binary 1011 = 1x2^3 + 0x2^2 + 1x2^1 + 1x2^0 = 8 + 0 + 2 + 1 = 11 in decimal." },
  { question: "How do you convert decimal to hexadecimal?", answer: "Repeatedly divide the decimal number by 16 and record each remainder. The remainders, read from bottom to top, form the hexadecimal number. Remainders 10-15 are represented by letters A-F. For example, 255 in decimal = FF in hexadecimal." },
  { question: "What is the octal number system?", answer: "The octal system is base 8, using digits 0-7. It was commonly used in early computing because it maps cleanly to groups of three binary digits. For example, binary 111 = octal 7, and binary 101010 = octal 52. Octal is still used in Unix file permissions." },
  { question: "Why do computers use binary?", answer: "Computers use binary (base 2) because digital circuits have two stable states: on and off, represented as 1 and 0. This maps directly to electrical voltage levels and makes hardware design reliable and simple. All data in a computer — text, images, video — is ultimately stored as sequences of binary digits (bits)." },
  { question: "What is hexadecimal used for?", answer: "Hexadecimal (base 16) is a compact way to represent binary data. Each hex digit corresponds to exactly 4 binary digits, so one byte (8 bits) is two hex digits. Hex is used for color codes in web design (#FF5733), memory addresses, MAC addresses, and debugging. It is much more readable than long binary strings." }
]) %>

